🔥 Per-Session Timing & Activity Features
total_duration
Role: Measures overall test time.

Cheaters with pre-knowledge: finish quickly (low total duration).

Active cheaters searching answers: might have longer duration or even timeout.

Normal users: moderate duration.

mean_time_per_question
Role: Overall speed metric.

Pre-knowledge cheaters: unusually low (answer fast).

Active cheaters: possibly high (due to tab switches/searching).

Normal: in the middle.

std_dev_time_per_question
Role: Measures time inconsistency.

Normal users: some variation (easy vs hard).

Pre-knowledge cheaters: very low variation (everything is fast).

Active cheaters: high variation (some normal, some delayed).

num_tab_switches
Role: Direct cheat signal.

Active cheaters will have higher count (tabbing out to search).

Normal and pre-knowledge users should have very low or zero.

num_answer_changes
Role: Measures reconsideration behavior.

Normal users often change answers.

Pre-knowledge cheaters: rarely change (they already "know").

Active cheaters: may change but not always.

num_revisits
Role: Captures if user revisited questions.

Normal users: revisit to double-check answers.

Cheaters: may skip revisits (pre-knowledge) or revisit more (active cheaters double-checking).

sequential_transition_rate
Role: Measures how linearly they went through questions.

Pre-knowledge: high rate (go question 1→2→3 fast).

Normal: lower (may jump around).

Active cheaters: may jump (searching tricky questions).

🔥 Per-Session Performance Features
accuracy
Role: Final correctness metric.

Pre-knowledge: near 100%.

Active cheaters: also high if successful.

Normal: variable.
⚠️ Note: Alone, it’s weak (some top students are also 100% correct!). It’s strong in combo with time/tab features.

accuracy_deviation
Role: Compares user’s score to what is expected.

If user scored much higher than expected based on question difficulty → suspicious (cheating).

A top student would score high but also show normal behavior in time/tab features → model learns difference.

🔥 Deviation Features (These are Key 🔑 — they make your model compare user to population)
mean_time_z_score
Role: Measures how much faster/slower user was compared to others.

Big negative = user is answering much faster (pre-knowledge).

Big positive = slower (possible active cheater struggling).

min_time_z_score
Role: Shows the fastest deviation per question.

If very negative → user was ultra-fast on at least one hard question → red flag for cheating.

max_time_z_score
Role: Shows slowest question (possible search or struggle).

High max value may indicate active cheater who searched an answer.

std_dev_time_z_score
Role: Measures consistency of deviation.

Pre-knowledge: consistently fast (low std_dev).

Active cheaters: inconsistent (some fast, some slow — depending on search time).

tab_switch_deviation
Role: Compares user tab switch count vs. expected (population avg).

High positive = user tabbing more than usual → red flag.

Normal users stay within range.



